Kenyan banks will take a full hit from provisions for new loans issued in 2019 and beyond after the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) refined its capital waiver rules. The banking sector regulator had earlier published draft guidelines, which proposed a five-year transition period during which incremental provisions may be added back to earnings for purposes of computing core capital. This came in the wake of adoption of more conservative International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS9) and which took effect on January 1. READ:Bad loans dim prospects of private sector